Descriptive Statistics Demo

Joshua M. Garcia

3/2/2021

This line of code is to install the jmv package that is integrated with jamovi. eval=FALSE means that this line will not run unless you manually tell it to. This is to avoid reinstalling each time this code is ran.

I also install the tableone, tidyverse, and kableExtra packages for later on.

install.packages('jmv')
install.packages('tableone')
install.packages('tidyverse')
install.packages('kableExtra')

Import Data

In this data chunk, I assign the iris data set to a data frame titled data. This will be stored in the Global Environment.

data <- iris

This command is to view the top of the data.

These next lines are copy and pasted from jamovi. Figure width and figure height are set to 50% to improve readability.

jmv::descriptives(
    data = data,
    vars = vars(Sepal.Length, Sepal.Width, Petal.Length, Petal.Width),
    hist = TRUE,
    dens = TRUE,
    box = TRUE,
    violin = TRUE,
    dot = TRUE,
    skew = TRUE,
    kurt = TRUE)

    formula = Sepal.Length + Sepal.Width + Petal.Length + Petal.Width ~ Species,
    data = data,
    hist = TRUE,
    dens = TRUE,

Comparison to Other Packages

Here, I demonstrate the package called tableone that helps make descriptive statistics tables.

t1 <- tableone::CreateTableOne(data = data)
table <- print(t1)
##                           
##                            Overall     
##   n                         150        
##   Sepal.Length (mean (SD)) 5.84 (0.83) 
##   Sepal.Width (mean (SD))  3.06 (0.44) 
##   Petal.Length (mean (SD)) 3.76 (1.77) 
##   Petal.Width (mean (SD))  1.20 (0.76) 
##   Species (%)                          
##      setosa                  50 (33.3) 
##      versicolor              50 (33.3) 
##      virginica               50 (33.3)
library(tidyverse)
library(kableExtra)
kable(table, caption = "Iris Data") %>%
   kable_styling(c("bordered","condensed"),
                latex_options = c("HOLD_position"), 
                font_size = 10,
                full_width = F)
Iris Data

Sneak peak for next time. Ggplot is a very flexible plotting program. Here I plot sepal length by sepal width split by species.

ggplot(data, aes(x=Sepal.Length, y=Sepal.Width, color=Species)) + geom_point() + geom_smooth()
